{"cursor":"16421","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\nIn user interface design, a 'mode' is a distinct setting within a computer\nprogram or any physical machine interface, in which the same user input will\nproduce perceived different results than it would in other settings. The best-\nknown modal interface components are probably the Caps lock and Insert keys on\nthe standard computer keyboard, both of which put the user's typing into a\ndifferent mode after being pressed, then return it to the regular mode after\nbeing re-pressed.\n\nAn interface that uses no modes is known as a 'modeless'\ninterface. [http://www.usabilityfirst.com/glossary/term_321.txl Usability\nGlossary: modeless] Modeless interfaces intend to avoid 'mode errors' [http://www.usabilityfirst.com/glossary/mode-\nerror/ Usability Glossary: mode error] by making it impossible for the\nuser to commit them.\n","linknr":259,"url":"Mode_(computer_interface)","recorded":1362552216,"links":14,"instances":["computing","javascript","editor","computing","computing","usability_consultant","computer_science"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Humanâ€“computer interaction","User interface techniques","User interfaces"],"headings":["Definition","Examples","Mode errors","Assessment","Design recommendations","See also","Notes","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1c/Wiki_letter_w_cropped.svg/20px-Wiki_letter_w_cropped.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9f/Arret.jpg/220px-Arret.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf9/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/poweredby_mediawiki_88x31.png"],"tags":[["interface","computing"],["state","computer_science"],["ex","editor"],["palette","computing"],["lightbox","javascript"],["jakob_nielsen","usability